<span style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;"><span style="font-family: Verdana;"><span style="font-size: 7pt;">According to The Economist, </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">we are perilously close to</span>__</span>** __a **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">war</span></span>** that may prove much more deadly than previous ones__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. One of the scenarios described by the magazine is fairly familiar. It involves Iran’s desire to acquire nuclear capacity and eventually a nuclear weapon and Israel’s desire to stop this at all costs. It is, however, the second scenario that is </span>__less discussed but perhaps more likely to engulf the region in an all out war__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. This second scenario </span>__is__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> about </span>__the frantic arms race that has been under way since the inconclusive war in 2006 between Israel and Hezbullah__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. The Turkish and international media is not paying much attention to what is going on between Iran, Syria and Hezbullah. Yet, </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">if Iran is squeezed </span>too much <span style="background: yellow;">by sanctions or feels that an Israeli attack is imminent, it will be</span>__ </span>**__the**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> <span style="background: yellow;">Lebanon</span> </span>**front -- **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">with Hezbullah as Tehran’s</span></span>** main **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">proxy</span></span>**<span style="background: yellow;"> -- **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">that may blow up first</span>**</span>__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. As The Economist puts it, </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span 