tom: 0in; padding-left: 0in; padding-right: 0in; padding-top: 0in;">A</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">tomic </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow; border-bottom: windowtext 1pt solid; border-left: windowtext 1pt solid; border-right: windowtext 1pt solid; border-top: windowtext 1pt solid; padding-bottom: 0in; padding-left: 0in; padding-right: 0in; padding-top: 0in;">E</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">nergy </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow; border-bottom: windowtext 1pt solid; border-left: windowtext 1pt solid; border-right: windowtext 1pt solid; border-top: windowtext 1pt solid; padding-bottom: 0in; padding-left: 0in; padding-right: 0in; padding-top: 0in;">A</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">gency, a watchdog arm of the United Nations that monitors the use of nuclear power and technology, </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">has documented 18 cases involving the theft</span> or loss <span style="background: yellow;">of plutonium or weapons-grade uranium</span>, mostly occurring in the former Soviet Union__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. The IAEA says a majority of these cases have not had a pre-identified buyer and "amateurish character" and "poor organization" have been the hallmark of some of the cases involving unauthorized possession of materials. In Prague last year, Obama said, "Black market trade in nuclear secrets and nuclear materials abound." Government efforts have been made to secure nuclear material in recent years. Last week, the National Nuclear Security Agency (NNSA) worked with officials in Chile to remove nuclear material from reactors near Santiago and transport it to the USA. The agency has removed all significant amounts of highly enriched uranium from 18 countries, helped convert 60 reactors in 32 countries to the use of safer, low-enriched ur